'''Justin R. Chin''' is a writer and artist. While working for [[LucasArts]], Chin wrote the storyline and acted as lead artist for ''[[Star Wars: Dark Forces]]'' and ''[[Star Wars: Jedi Knight: Dark Forces II]]''. The [[Star Wars Legends|Expanded Universe]] elements of [[Kyle Katarn]], [[Dark trooper]]s and various weapons such as the [[Bryar pistol/Legends|Bryar pistol]], are credited to him.
==Biography==
Chin had worked as animator, art director and writer for several video games of [[Wikipedia:Accolade (company)|Accolade, Inc.]] and other companies. In his previous experiences, he had seen until joining the ''[[Star Wars: Dark Forces]]'' team in December, [[1993]].<ref name="guide">''[[Dark Forces Official Player's Guide]]''</ref>

While initially ''Dark Forces'' was conceived as a story that followed the established canon, Chin thought that the 3-d engine could tell new stories, and described the original idea about "a special force of Stormtroopers" to [[Ray Gresko]] and [[Daron Stinnett]]. Believing that they needed a "single clear vision" from the start on which to work, he produced the first design document describing the characters, and a layout of 32 missions, each with a different objective, and set on a different [[planet/Legends|planet]], with its own look at feel. He provided pencil art concept sketches, which were further elaborated on by the computer artists.<ref name="guide" />

Focused on the game's look and feel, he treated the game as an action film, and spent some time studying video cassettes with films such as [[Wikipedia:Die Hard (film series)|''Die Hard'']] and [[Wikipedia:List of James Bond films|''James Bond'']], after which he produced some maps, puzzles and situations the action hero had to survive, which he then forwarded to the level designers.<ref name="guide" />

He currently works at Telltale games as an executive producer.

